A CSS selector is the part of a CSS rule that selects the content you want to style. The main types of selectors are listed below.

Universal selector: matches every element on a page, like a wildcard. In the example below, the styles apply to every element on the page.

* {
  color: green;
  font-size: 20px;
  line-height: 25px;
}

Element (type) selector: matches every HTML element of a given tag name. The styles below apply to every <ul> element on the page.

ul {
  list-style: none;
  border: solid 1px #ccc;
}

ID selector: matches an HTML element by its id attribute. The styles below apply to the element with id="container".

#container {
  width: 960px;
  margin: 0 auto;
}

<div id="container"></div>

Class selector: matches every element whose class attribute contains the given class name. The styles below apply to every element with class="box".

.box {
  padding: 10px;
  margin: 10px;
  width: 240px;
}

<div class="box"></div>

Descendant combinator: combines two or more selectors so that the rule applies only to elements that are descendants of the first selector. The descendant does not have to be an immediate child - it can be nested arbitrarily deep.

#container .box {

float: left;
padding-bottom: 15px;

}

<div id="container">

<div class="box"></div>

<div class="box-2"></div>

</div>

<div class="box"></div>

This rule applies to every element with class "box" that is inside the element with id "container", at any depth.

Child combinator: similar to the descendant combinator, but only targets immediate children.

#container > .box {

float: left;
padding-bottom: 15px;

}

<div id="container">

<div class="box"></div>

<div>

<div class="box"></div>

</div>

</div>

The rule matches only elements with class "box" that are direct children of #container; the nested .box inside the inner <div> is not matched.

General sibling combinator: matches elements that share a parent and appear after the first selector in the source order.

h2 ~ p {

margin-bottom: 20px;

}

<h2>Title</h2>
<p>Paragraph example.</p>
<p>Paragraph example.</p>
<p>Paragraph example.</p>
<div class="box">

<p>Paragraph example.</p>

</div>

Every <p> that is a sibling of an <h2> (and comes after it) is styled. Other elements between the <h2> and the <p> do not break the relationship.

Adjacent sibling combinator: uses the + symbol and is similar to the general sibling combinator, except that the target element must be the immediate next sibling.

p + p {

text-indent: 1.5em;
margin-bottom: 0;

}

<h2>Title</h2>
<p>Paragraph example.</p>
<p>Paragraph example.</p>
<p>Paragraph example.</p>

<div class="box">

<p>Paragraph example.</p>
<p>Paragraph example.</p>

</div>

The rule applies only to <p> elements that immediately follow another <p>. The first <p> on a page does not receive the styles, and if another element appears between two paragraphs, the rule does not match.

Attribute selector: targets elements based on the presence or value of an HTML attribute, declared using square brackets.

input[type="text"] {

background-color: #444;
width: 200px;

}

<input type="text">

A CSS preprocessor is a tool that extends the basic functionality of vanilla CSS through its own scripting language, adding features such as variables, functions, mixins, nesting, and inheritance. The preprocessor compiles its source files into plain CSS.

Sass: short for Syntactically Awesome Style Sheets. Sass can be written in two different syntaxes: the older indented .sass syntax, or the newer .scss syntax.

Sass vs SCSS

Sass is based on indentation; SCSS (Sassy CSS) is not.
Sass uses the .sass extension; SCSS uses .scss.
Sass omits curly braces and semicolons; SCSS uses them, just like CSS.

SASS Syntax

$font-color: #fff
$bg-color: #00f

#box

color: $font-color
background: $bg-color

SCSS Syntax

$font-color: #fff;
$bg-color: #00f;

#box {

color: $font-color;
background: $bg-color;

}

Less: short for Leaner Style Sheets. Less can be added to any JavaScript project via npm or the less.js file, and uses the .less extension.

Less syntax is similar to SCSS, with a few differences. For example, Less uses @ to declare variables.

@font-color: #fff;
@bg-color: #00f;

#box {

color: @font-color;
background: @bg-color;

}

Stylus: Stylus offers a great deal of syntactic flexibility - it supports native CSS as well as omitting brackets, colons, and semicolons. It does not use @ or $ for declaring variables.

/* Stylus written like native CSS */
font-color = #fff;
bg-color = #00f;

#box {

color: font-color;
background: bg-color;

}

/* OR */

/* Stylus without curly braces */
font-color = #fff;
bg-color = #00f;

#box

color: font-color;
background: bg-color;

Pseudo-classes select regular elements, but only under certain conditions - for example, when the user is hovering over a link.

:link
:visited
:hover
:active
:focus

In the example below, the color is applied to the anchor tag while the mouse is over it.

/* mouse over link */
a:hover {

color: #FF00FF;

}

Pseudo-elements, on the other hand, let you style parts of an element that do not exist as separate nodes in the document tree - for example, the first letter of a paragraph, or content inserted before or after an element.

::before
::after
::first-letter
::first-line
::selection

In the example below, only the first line of every paragraph receives the styles.

p::first-line {

color: #FF0000;
font-variant: small-caps;

}

Centering with a table

HTML:

<div class="cn"><div class="inner">your content</div></div>

CSS:

.cn {

display: table-cell;
width: 500px;
height: 500px;
vertical-align: middle;
text-align: center;

}

.inner {

display: inline-block;
width: 200px; height: 200px;

}

Centering with transform

HTML:

<div class="cn"><div class="inner">your content</div></div>

CSS:

.cn {

position: relative;
width: 500px;
height: 500px;

}

.inner {

position: absolute;
top: 50%; left: 50%;
transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
width: 200px;
height: 200px;

}

Centering with flexbox

HTML:

<div class="cn"><div class="inner">your content</div></div>

CSS:

.cn {

display: flex;
justify-content: center;
align-items: center;

}

Centering with grid

HTML:

<div class="wrap-grid">
<div class="inner">your content</div>
</div>

CSS:

.wrap-grid {

display: grid;
place-content: center;

}

The CSS3 calc() function lets you perform arithmetic on property values. Instead of declaring a static value (for example, a fixed pixel width for an element), you can use calc() to express the value as the result of adding, subtracting, multiplying, or dividing two or more numeric values.

.foo {

width: calc(100px + 50px);

}

Custom properties (also called CSS variables or cascading variables) are user-defined values that can be reused throughout a document. A variable is declared using the -- prefix and its value is read using the var() function.

:root {

--main-bg-color: brown;

}

.one {

color: white;
background-color: var(--main-bg-color);

margin: 10px;
width: 50px;
height: 50px;
display: inline-block;

}

A declaration marked with !important has the highest precedence in the cascade and overrides any normally cascaded value for that property.

 p {
   color: red !important;
 }
 #thing {
   color: green;
 }

 <p id="thing">Will be RED.</p>

Progressive rendering refers to techniques for improving a webpage's performance - particularly its perceived load time - by rendering content for display as quickly as possible.

One common approach is lazy loading images. The Intersection Observer API makes it easy to detect when an element enters the viewport, so you can defer loading the full-resolution image until that point.

A sample snippet is given below.

<img class="lazy" src="placeholder-image.jpg" data-src="image-to-lazy-load-1x.jpg" data-srcset="image-to-lazy-load-2x.jpg 2x, image-to-lazy-load-1x.jpg 1x" alt="I'm an image!">

document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", function() {
  var lazyImages = [].slice.call(document.querySelectorAll("img.lazy"));

  if ("IntersectionObserver" in window) {
    let lazyImageObserver = new IntersectionObserver(function(entries, observer) {
      entries.forEach(function(entry) {
        if (entry.isIntersecting) {
          let lazyImage = entry.target;
          lazyImage.src = lazyImage.dataset.src;
          lazyImage.srcset = lazyImage.dataset.srcset;
          lazyImage.classList.remove("lazy");
          lazyImageObserver.unobserve(lazyImage);
        }
      });
    });

    lazyImages.forEach(function(lazyImage) {
      lazyImageObserver.observe(lazyImage);
    });
  } else {
    // Possibly fall back to event handlers here
  }
});

The @supports rule in CSS can be used to check whether the current browser supports a given feature, and apply rules conditionally.

@supports (display: grid) {

div {

display: grid;

}

}
